to see him settle in as well.

473
00:23:34.331 --> 00:23:36.791
Because even as his character
was settling in. you know.

474
00:23:36.875 --> 00:23:39.711
he had his own version of that too.

475
00:23:40.420 --> 00:23:42.464
And so.
especially in the scenes in the finale.

476
00:23:42.547 --> 00:23:46.676
you can really see him.
like. shining. which we love.

477
00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:47.844
It's really cool.

478
00:23:49.220 --> 00:23:51.140
You're right.
You know. what's been said about...

479
00:23:52.515 --> 00:23:56.686
if you just look at even the bridge and
what Special Effects does and it looks...

480
00:23:56.936 --> 00:23:59.481
it's beautiful and it's almost effortless.

481
00:23:59.564 --> 00:24:01.566
but it's hard to be at that level

482
00:24:01.650 --> 00:24:05.695
and be safe in such a small room.
essentially. with these explosions.

483
00:24:05.779 --> 00:24:10.784
I'm just curious. What is it like. as
an actor. to be in a room like the bridge.

484
00:24:10.867 --> 00:24:12.535
have multiple explosions going off.

485
00:24:12.619 --> 00:24:14.954
you've got people all around...

486
00:24:15.038 --> 00:24:18.166
Yo. I'll say this.
I'll say something quick.

487
00:24:18.249 --> 00:24:21.044
'cause. David. I really wanna hear
what you have to say too.

488
00:24:21.127 --> 00:24:22.796
It's exciting.

489
00:24:24.839 --> 00:24:28.051
You know. like. that's. like.
the main word I can think of.

490
00:24:28.134 --> 00:24:32.972
It's so kinetic and dynamic and exciting

491
00:24:33.056 --> 00:24:36.476
and yes. you gotta be on top of it. right?

492
00:24:36.559 --> 00:24:40.438
But there is something so exciting
and fulfilling about that.

493
00:24:40.522 --> 00:24:43.650
I can only imagine for...
Rachael. we love her so much.

494
00:24:44.609 --> 00:24:48.863
And I can only imagine
what it's like for somebody like Doug

495
00:24:48.947 --> 00:24:54.119
who also has to do all of that
behind all of that rubber and latex

496
00:24:54.202 --> 00:24:57.038
and imbue all that life
in the midst of these circumstances.

497
00:24:57.122 --> 00:24:58.790
in the midst of these explosions.

498
00:24:58.873 --> 00:25:01.042
with the lines... with the charac...

499
00:25:01.126 --> 00:25:02.812
with the life of the character
and everything.

500
00:25:02.836 --> 00:25:04.379
It's. like. he's a master.

501
00:25:04.462 --> 00:25:07.924
And even David Tomlinson as well
with Linus. you know.

502
00:25:08.007 --> 00:25:11.803
the fact that they're able to do it
through all of the prosthetic...

503
00:25:14.889 --> 00:25:17.350
it's just... it's really phenomenal.

504
00:25:17.434 --> 00:25:18.893
but it's a lot of fun.

505
00:25:20.937 --> 00:25:22.522
You will be better.

506
00:25:22.605 --> 00:25:28.486
You cannot not improve
from being thrown into that scenario.

507
00:25:29.154 --> 00:25:30.321
I'm so happy you said that.

508
00:25:30.405 --> 00:25:31.448
I couldn't agree more.

509
00:25:33.950 --> 00:25:36.703
I think it makes you
a better actor overall.

510
00:25:37.704 --> 00:25:40.081
Piggybacking off of
what Sonequa was saying.

511
00:25:40.165 --> 00:25:45.420
is you really have to embrace it all.

512
00:25:45.503 --> 00:25:46.504
Yeah.

513
00:25:46.588 --> 00:25:48.548
But then. trust in the camera work

514
00:25:48.631 --> 00:25:50.467
and the environment to do the work

515
00:25:50.550 --> 00:25:54.220
and not play what's being presented
on the camera.

516
00:25:54.304 --> 00:25:56.931
I really try
to lean into the micro moments

517
00:25:57.015 --> 00:25:59.517
when doing these scenes on the bridge

518
00:25:59.601 --> 00:26:01.895
when we have explosions
and there's a lot going on.

519
00:26:02.645 --> 00:26:06.900
Dare I say. I think it made it easier
as an actor to do my job

520
00:26:06.983 --> 00:26:11.613
because there was less to
have to reproduce. recreate all around me.

521
00:26:12.447 --> 00:26:15.283
Trusting the...
trusting in the simplicity of it

522
00:26:15.909 --> 00:26:18.578
was definitely my way to navigate it all

523
00:26:18.661 --> 00:26:20.413
and also not taking anything for granted.

524
00:26:21.080 --> 00:26:23.583
Tunde said. "Every inch matters." I agree.

525
00:26:24.375 --> 00:26:25.668
Every inch matters

526
00:26:25.752 --> 00:26:29.506
and every moment
is worth holding and releasing.

527
00:26:31.216 --> 00:26:32.592
Jumping off of what you both said.

528
00:26:32.675 --> 00:26:36.221
a huge shout-out to Darcy
and our Special Effects team

529
00:26:36.304 --> 00:26:40.934
because they're the ones who.
you know. set all of that up

530
00:26:41.017 --> 00:26:43.269
so that... and always make sure it's safe.

531
00:26:44.103 --> 00:26:47.440
so that you guys can do what you do
and they're awesome.

532
00:26:47.524 --> 00:26:49.108
I gotta second that. you know.

533
00:26:50.819 --> 00:26:53.780
Darcy has had five seasons of awesomeness.

534
00:26:53.863 --> 00:26:55.073
Yeah.

535
00:26:55.156 --> 00:26:58.409
That DNA is spreading
to the other <i>Star Trek</i> shows as well.

536
00:26:58.493 --> 00:27:01.996
and. you know.
his number two on the floor there. Greg.

537
00:27:02.664 --> 00:27:05.917
who's just been fantastic. you know...

538
00:27:08.044 --> 00:27:10.004
our well-being is in his hands every day

539
00:27:11.005 --> 00:27:12.715
that the things are happening.

540
00:27:12.799 --> 00:27:14.467
And they're the glue. Special Effects.

541
00:27:14.551 --> 00:27:17.470
You have visual effects.
It's a visual effects show. visually.

542
00:27:17.554 --> 00:27:19.764
And then you've got special effects.
That's the glue.

543
00:27:20.390 --> 00:27:21.784
They're used in every single scene.

544
00:27:21.808 --> 00:27:24.143
whether it be atmo here on the AR wall

545
00:27:24.227 --> 00:27:27.397
to help blend
the digital with the reality.

546
00:27:28.064 --> 00:27:31.025
or whether it be the explosions
on the bridge or the fire planet.

547
00:27:31.109 --> 00:27:33.611
you know. they're always present
in some way or another.

548
00:27:36.489 --> 00:27:39.049
For this scene here. Tunde.
can you remind me how many flowers...

549
00:27:39.534 --> 00:27:41.411
We had to order those flowers
way in advance.

550
00:27:41.494 --> 00:27:44.789
- We had 35.000 flowers.
- Thirty-five thousand.

551
00:27:44.873 --> 00:27:46.499
- What?
- Yeah. and remember.

552
00:27:46.583 --> 00:27:49.586
that was one of those moments
when we said we needed flowers

553
00:27:49.669 --> 00:27:54.966
and we were expecting. "Well. we can't
possibly get that many flowers."

554
00:27:55.049 --> 00:27:56.050
And they...

555
00:27:56.134 --> 00:27:57.260
What Doug said...

556
00:27:57.343 --> 00:28:01.764
Doug. Production Design. said.
"Leave it with me. I'll figure it out."

557
00:28:01.848 --> 00:28:02.849
- You know?
- Yeah.

558
00:28:02.932 --> 00:28:03.933
And it was like...

559
00:28:06.477 --> 00:28:07.812
Oh. my goodness.

560
00:28:08.688 --> 00:28:10.023
When and how...

561
00:28:10.106 --> 00:28:11.107
How did you...

562
00:28:11.190 --> 00:28:14.736
Where do you get 35.000 flowers from?

563
00:28:16.487 --> 00:28:18.823
- I wish I knew.
- They grew them in the parking lot.

564
00:28:18.907 --> 00:28:20.158
No. I'm just kidding.

565
00:28:23.494 --> 00:28:27.624
They found a house somewhere overseas.

566
00:28:27.707 --> 00:28:29.751
and. remember. Michelle. they were like.

567
00:28:29.834 --> 00:28:32.128
"Okay. you have to choose
what color you want

568
00:28:32.211 --> 00:28:34.422
and what type you want
by this specific day

569
00:28:34.505 --> 00:28:37.383
if we're gonna be able to have them
in time to be able to test them

570
00:28:37.467 --> 00:28:39.302
and be able to put them in the movie."

571
00:28:39.385 --> 00:28:41.054
- Wow.
- And it was so far in advance.

572
00:28:41.137 --> 00:28:44.515
I think we were still in the process
of designing the set at that point.

573
00:28:44.599 --> 00:28:46.935
but we had to land on the flower color.

574
00:28:47.018 --> 00:28:49.312
That's right. Yeah. it was before
we had an actual concept

575
00:28:49.395 --> 00:28:50.605
- that we had to pick.
- Yeah.

576
00:28:50.688 --> 00:28:51.731
Yeah.

577
00:28:51.814 --> 00:28:54.442
- Wow.
- Wow.

578
00:28:55.360 --> 00:28:59.614
But that's the thing about this team.
is. you know. if we need something.

579
00:28:59.697 --> 00:29:03.576
the bar is so high.
but it's never impossible. you know?

580
00:29:03.660 --> 00:29:04.576
Yeah.

581
00:29:04.577 --> 00:29:07.957
Everyone always finds
a way and does it.

582
00:29:08.039 --> 00:29:09.624
Yeah. Right.

583
00:29:10.375 --> 00:29:13.044
Everybody shows up
and shows out every time.

584
00:29:13.127 --> 00:29:15.588
Such a wonderful gift
to be able to do the audio.

585
00:29:15.672 --> 00:29:17.382
'cause as I'm learning so much.

586
00:29:17.465 --> 00:29:19.717
our fans and family
who are listening to this...

587
00:29:20.385 --> 00:29:22.971
They get these very rich insights.

588
00:29:23.596 --> 00:29:25.556
I was just gonna say briefly.

589
00:29:25.640 --> 00:29:31.646
they just did a shot of L'ak.
and that's not actually Elias in there.

590
00:29:31.729 --> 00:29:34.857
That's a double.

591
00:29:35.483 --> 00:29:38.069
But with the facial prosthetic.
it looks exactly like him.

592
00:29:38.152 --> 00:29:40.530
- Wow.
- Wow. Yeah.

593
00:29:43.032 --> 00:29:44.659
You sneaky. you.

594
00:29:44.742 --> 00:29:45.743
Yeah.

595
00:29:46.953 --> 00:29:48.287
By the way. this isn't Eve.

596
00:29:48.371 --> 00:29:50.248
No. I'm just kidding. It's actually Eve.

597
00:29:50.748 --> 00:29:51.958
It's actually you.

598
00:29:53.668 --> 00:29:54.668
Oh. man.

599
00:29:56.170 --> 00:29:59.632
Shout-out to her here and you. Sonequa.

600
00:29:59.716 --> 00:30:01.092
and David and all of our actors

601
00:30:01.175 --> 00:30:05.346
because. you know. we have concepts for
what some of these things might look like.

602
00:30:05.430 --> 00:30:10.852
but all of you have to act against
something that is pretend in the moment.

603
00:30:10.935 --> 00:30:14.772
and you don't have
the final visual effects in your head.

604
00:30:14.856 --> 00:30:16.649
And to be able to do that

605
00:30:16.733 --> 00:30:20.945
with just an artistic rendering
of what it's eventually gonna look like.

606
00:30:21.029 --> 00:30:23.424
and then have it be so seamless
once the visual effects go in.

607
00:30:23.448 --> 00:30:25.616
it's always just phenomenal to me

608
00:30:25.700 --> 00:30:27.827
the way you all do that
and bring it to life.

609
00:30:27.910 --> 00:30:29.454
I have a question about that.

610
00:30:29.537 --> 00:30:31.056
I think Props were showing you. Sonequa.

611
00:30:31.080 --> 00:30:33.458
the shape
that the triangles needed to be in.

612
00:30:34.584 --> 00:30:38.546
And then the report I got back was.

613
00:30:38.629 --> 00:30:42.258
"She interrupted me while showing her.
and she figured it out.

614
00:30:42.341 --> 00:30:45.344
She just figured it out on her"...
So for you. the triangle...

615
00:30:46.220 --> 00:30:49.932
I've been wanting to ask you this
for a year now. Was it. like. no big deal?

616
00:30:50.016 --> 00:30:50.932
Like. was it...

617
00:30:50.933 --> 00:30:53.455
It was funny 'cause when we tried it.
we could barely figure it out.

618
00:30:53.478 --> 00:30:54.479
It was always a thing.

619
00:30:54.562 --> 00:30:56.981
and we were like.
"Okay. if we can barely figure it out.

620
00:30:57.065 --> 00:31:00.318
we gotta figure out. like.
how is she gonna do it on camera?"

621
00:31:00.401 --> 00:31:01.402
You know what I mean?

622
00:31:01.486 --> 00:31:03.863
So when you just came and you just...

623
00:31:04.489 --> 00:31:08.117
That is so funny.
and I did not even remember that.

624
00:31:08.201 --> 00:31:11.954
Mario is our brilliant props master.
Been with us from day one.

625
00:31:12.038 --> 00:31:14.749
And. you know. he probably just
really explained it real good

626
00:31:14.832 --> 00:31:16.751
and kind of set me up for success.

627
00:31:17.502 --> 00:31:19.087
Probably what happened.

628
00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:20.588
'Cause it was never a thing.

629
00:31:20.671 --> 00:31:23.633
'Cause we always obsess over the things
that could be things. right?

630
00:31:23.716 --> 00:31:24.634
Yeah.

631
00:31:24.635 --> 00:31:27.929
It was really interesting to me that
that was not a thing. you know?

632
00:31:28.012 --> 00:31:30.098
- You just came in and did it. you know?
- Yeah.

633
00:31:30.181 --> 00:31:33.518
And thank you also for letting me do
that Vulcan meditation pose

634
00:31:33.601 --> 00:31:34.602
to get into it.

635
00:31:34.685 --> 00:31:37.522
I always wanted to. like. throw in
little Vulcan things here and there.

636
00:31:37.605 --> 00:31:40.108
and you graciously let me
throw that one in there.

637
00:31:40.191 --> 00:31:42.377
I was like. "Let's call back the Vulcan
just for a second."

638
00:31:42.401 --> 00:31:43.486
Awesome.

639
00:31:44.487 --> 00:31:48.991
I'm just gonna do one quick shout-out
to one of our writers

640
00:31:49.075 --> 00:31:52.328
and co-EPs on the show. Alan McElroy.

641
00:31:52.411 --> 00:31:54.372
who's wonderful and has been on the show...

642
00:31:54.455 --> 00:31:59.460
like. he's a <i>Star Trek</i> guy
and such a science head.

643
00:31:59.544 --> 00:32:05.424
And he was the one who suggested
the basis for the design of that...

644
00:32:05.508 --> 00:32:08.845
it's a Mandelbrot...
I think is how it's pronounced.

645
00:32:08.928 --> 00:32:12.807
And the design of the thing...
the portal. basically...

646
00:32:14.475 --> 00:32:16.602
I will get it wrong
if I try to explain it.

647
00:32:16.686 --> 00:32:18.980
so just look up Mandelbrot.

648
00:32:19.063 --> 00:32:21.983
But it's a really cool shape.

649
00:32:22.066 --> 00:32:24.610
- and there's some significance to it.
- Yes.

650
00:32:24.694 --> 00:32:26.070
And it's just such a cool...

651
00:32:26.154 --> 00:32:29.157
that. like. that became the basis
for what this portal looks like

652
00:32:29.240 --> 00:32:33.202
and the way it overlaps kind of
on each other in a really neat way.

653
00:32:35.371 --> 00:32:37.540
That's beautiful. There's some...

654
00:32:37.623 --> 00:32:39.750
That's especially beautiful.

655
00:32:39.834 --> 00:32:41.043
We love Alan so much.

656
00:32:41.127 --> 00:32:43.379
I also feel like he did
such a phenomenal job

657
00:32:43.462 --> 00:32:44.672
on episode 2 of this season.

658
00:32:44.755 --> 00:32:47.800
I mean. all the episodes that he wrote.
but especially episode 2...

659
00:32:47.884 --> 00:32:50.344
it really touched me...
from this final season.

660
00:32:50.428 --> 00:32:53.431
But the Mandelbrot
has this divinity to it as well.

661
00:32:53.514 --> 00:32:57.977
which is so apropos for this season.

662
00:32:58.060 --> 00:33:00.521
So that is so dope. that he...

663
00:33:02.148 --> 00:33:04.233
- Yeah.
- ...that he came up with that.

664
00:33:04.317 --> 00:33:05.443
I love that.

665
00:33:07.236 --> 00:33:09.655
I was just gonna say
to you guys as compliment...

666
00:33:09.739 --> 00:33:11.616
or thank you for that.

667
00:33:12.408 --> 00:33:15.119
I was just looking at everybody
like Orville and Patrick

668
00:33:16.412 --> 00:33:17.788
and Mary and just...

669
00:33:17.872 --> 00:33:21.209
I think a big part of it...
David. I know you would agree with me...

670
00:33:22.793 --> 00:33:26.547
like you said. every single moment counts.
and us being able to. you know...

671
00:33:27.131 --> 00:33:30.009
us being able to imagine
this life with each other...

672
00:33:32.011 --> 00:33:33.596
it makes such a difference.

673
00:33:33.679 --> 00:33:35.514
and it really settles us.

674
00:33:35.598 --> 00:33:39.644
It cements us
in the authenticity of this world.

675
00:33:39.727 --> 00:33:45.233
that we're in this wild.
imagined life together. you know?

676
00:33:45.316 --> 00:33:46.609
Yeah.

677
00:33:46.692 --> 00:33:47.777
Absolutely.

678
00:33:48.694 --> 00:33:51.155
- I always felt very held.
- Yes!

679
00:33:51.239 --> 00:33:53.950
I just felt very well supported. you know?

680
00:33:54.033 --> 00:33:55.743
And even when I've mentioned something.

681
00:33:55.826 --> 00:33:58.496
they always encouraged us
to just aim high.

682
00:33:58.579 --> 00:34:02.333
It felt completely supportive
in every moment.

683
00:34:02.416 --> 00:34:03.459
And also. as well.

684
00:34:03.542 --> 00:34:05.920
listen. there were some days
when playing these scenes.

685
00:34:06.003 --> 00:34:09.090
I was thinking. "What the heck am I doing?
This is wild.

686
00:34:09.173 --> 00:34:10.758
It's not making any sense."

687
00:34:10.841 --> 00:34:12.760
This is happening and that's happening.

688
00:34:12.843 --> 00:34:16.597
and the absurdity of it all.
I find hilarious.

689
00:34:16.681 --> 00:34:18.015
Hilarious.

690
00:34:18.099 --> 00:34:19.475
- It is.
- Ridiculous.

691
00:34:19.558 --> 00:34:21.602
I love the challenge of that.

692
00:34:21.686 --> 00:34:23.688
just trusting and letting go

693
00:34:23.771 --> 00:34:26.148
and just immersing yourself
with what's in front of you.

694
00:34:26.232 --> 00:34:27.775
or not in front of you.

695
00:34:37.285 --> 00:34:38.744
Doug Jones.

696
00:34:38.828 --> 00:34:39.829
Action Saru.

697
00:34:39.912 --> 00:34:42.832
- Action Saru.
- Saru right there.

698
00:34:42.915 --> 00:34:45.876
By the way. I also wanna say.

699
00:34:45.960 --> 00:34:49.964
one of the things. among the many.
that we all love about you. Sonequa...

700
00:34:50.047 --> 00:34:54.176
I'm just gonna give some love your way

701
00:34:54.927 --> 00:34:58.597
and just say I really appreciate

702
00:34:58.681 --> 00:35:02.226
how you always appreciate
every single person.

703
00:35:02.310 --> 00:35:05.104
every single cast member. our crew.

704
00:35:06.605 --> 00:35:08.941
Like. I notice
as we're going through this commentary.

