we're going through this commentary.

721
00:35:55.446 --> 00:35:58.282
and you're noting everyone.

722
00:35:58.366 --> 00:36:02.703
because everyone does contribute
and. you know.

723
00:36:02.787 --> 00:36:07.416
that's a really wonderful thing
to notice and comment on

724
00:36:07.500 --> 00:36:09.585
and notice what everyone brings to it.

725
00:36:09.668 --> 00:36:11.712
And that's just lovely.

726
00:36:11.796 --> 00:36:14.423
And you do that with everyone on the set.

727
00:36:14.507 --> 00:36:15.716
Absolutely.

728
00:36:15.800 --> 00:36:17.093
That is the truth.

729
00:36:17.927 --> 00:36:20.262
It makes a difference...
makes a difference. right?

730
00:36:20.346 --> 00:36:22.056
When people come to work every day

731
00:36:22.139 --> 00:36:25.476
and they know that
that consistency is there.

732
00:36:25.559 --> 00:36:26.685
Yeah.

733
00:36:26.769 --> 00:36:28.521
It changes... It changes everything.

734
00:36:28.604 --> 00:36:31.190
Because we've all been in situations
where it's not there.

735
00:36:31.273 --> 00:36:32.233
- you know...
- Yeah.

736
00:36:32.234 --> 00:36:33.960
...on different shows
that we've been a part of

737
00:36:33.984 --> 00:36:35.403
over our careers. right?

738
00:36:36.028 --> 00:36:38.155
And that's hard. Now. the shows are hard.

739
00:36:38.239 --> 00:36:40.866
Movies... Television shows
are hard to make as they are

740
00:36:40.950 --> 00:36:42.493
just normally. right?

741
00:36:43.285 --> 00:36:48.833
And... But when you have a leader
who is making everybody feel at home

742
00:36:48.916 --> 00:36:51.961
and who actually cares about
what everyone is going through.

743
00:36:52.795 --> 00:36:54.505
and who they are as people.

744
00:36:55.131 --> 00:36:57.258
it changes... it changes everything.

745
00:36:58.050 --> 00:36:59.176
Absolutely.

746
00:36:59.260 --> 00:37:02.388
Thank you all so much.
It was... I was blessed to do it.

747
00:37:02.471 --> 00:37:05.975
I... God really blessed me and...

748
00:37:06.058 --> 00:37:09.019
and it was such an honor too. you know.

749
00:37:09.103 --> 00:37:10.771
Like. this group of people. man.

750
00:37:11.605 --> 00:37:13.941
It was so easy. you know.

751
00:37:14.024 --> 00:37:17.653
and that's also not something
we experience very often. right?

752
00:37:18.154 --> 00:37:19.155
Yeah.

753
00:37:20.281 --> 00:37:24.535
But. yeah. everybody...
It's just a phenomenal group of people.

754
00:37:24.618 --> 00:37:26.912
But thank you. guys.

755
00:37:26.996 --> 00:37:31.375
My absolute privilege and joy to be
a part of this journey with you guys.

756
00:37:31.459 --> 00:37:34.378
- Yeah.
- Truly. truly. Yeah. absolutely.

757
00:37:34.462 --> 00:37:38.299
Yeah. It's a long journey.
you know. that we've been on.

758
00:37:38.382 --> 00:37:41.093
And you know. it's...

759
00:37:41.177 --> 00:37:43.971
What was so unique for me
in this journey was.

760
00:37:45.306 --> 00:37:47.433
you know. meeting Alex for the first time.

761
00:37:48.267 --> 00:37:52.688
And. you know. we actually met
in a bathroom for the first time.

762
00:37:52.771 --> 00:37:56.734
And it's a funny. funny story.
I'll save it for another... another time.

763
00:37:56.817 --> 00:37:58.611
But what I really appreciated

764
00:37:58.694 --> 00:38:01.071
was just this creating...
him creating a space

765
00:38:01.155 --> 00:38:06.035
where we all felt like we could
do our biggest and most epic work.

766
00:38:06.118 --> 00:38:07.661
whatever that may be.

767
00:38:07.745 --> 00:38:10.831
Because often in television
and in movies. it's very rare

768
00:38:10.915 --> 00:38:15.628
that you're able to reach for the stars
and say anything is possible.

769
00:38:16.128 --> 00:38:18.380
And so to have an environment
that was created.

770
00:38:19.173 --> 00:38:22.635
and a universe that was created.
that allowed us to do that type of thing.

771
00:38:22.718 --> 00:38:25.387
was just. you know...

772
00:38:25.471 --> 00:38:29.517
This is...
It's a once-in-a-lifetime experience and...

773
00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:31.810
and to merge that with <i>Trek.</i>
you know. and he...

774
00:38:31.894 --> 00:38:35.731
and he wrote the reboot of <i>Trek.</i>
It came out in the movies. you know.

775
00:38:36.607 --> 00:38:42.071
It's quite a universe that...
that he allowed us to come play in.

776
00:38:42.154 --> 00:38:43.155
Yeah.

777
00:38:43.239 --> 00:38:46.825
Well said. Tunde.
He's an absolute visionary.

778
00:38:47.493 --> 00:38:50.871
He is way more brilliant
than a lot of people even understand.

779
00:38:50.955 --> 00:38:56.835
and the way he brought cinema
to our iteration especially.

780
00:38:56.919 --> 00:39:01.799
And I just... I just... I ditto.
I ditto everything you said.

781
00:39:01.882 --> 00:39:06.220
Also speaking from... speaking from. like...

782
00:39:06.303 --> 00:39:10.099
speaking about leading from kindness
as well. you know.

783
00:39:11.016 --> 00:39:12.393
Such an inspiring...

784
00:39:12.476 --> 00:39:15.771
He was such an inspiring leader as well.
just like the two of you.

785
00:39:17.940 --> 00:39:21.902
Yeah. I remember watching him
over the years in certain times

786
00:39:22.152 --> 00:39:26.240
and just being... just being floored
by what he's capable of.

787
00:39:26.323 --> 00:39:32.162
and. you know. by what he...
what he poured in here into our story.

788
00:39:33.038 --> 00:39:37.585
Yeah. Sonequa. you were saying
that he's more brilliant than people know.

789
00:39:37.668 --> 00:39:44.383
He really is and he's...
he's so kind. like. he's...

790
00:39:45.050 --> 00:39:48.470
he's kind and generous and thoughtful

791
00:39:48.554 --> 00:39:53.642
and he's. you know. like all of you.
like everyone on the show.

792
00:39:53.726 --> 00:39:56.437
he's someone who wants
to lift up those around him

793
00:39:56.520 --> 00:39:59.106
and create opportunities and. you know.

794
00:39:59.898 --> 00:40:03.569
he created an opportunity for me
to come in and do this.

795
00:40:03.652 --> 00:40:07.823
and it's been just the best experience.

796
00:40:07.906 --> 00:40:10.284
I mean. I just... I'm so grateful for it.

797
00:40:11.535 --> 00:40:17.458
He's really just a wonderful mentor.
friend. human being. colleague.

798
00:40:17.541 --> 00:40:18.959
all the things.

799
00:40:21.378 --> 00:40:22.880
Oh. my goodness.

800
00:40:24.006 --> 00:40:25.007
So true.

801
00:40:25.799 --> 00:40:29.470
And here's our Progenitor. Here she is.

802
00:40:29.553 --> 00:40:31.930
That's Somkele. I think.

803
00:40:32.014 --> 00:40:34.224
If I butcher her name
I apologize. Somkele.

804
00:40:34.308 --> 00:40:36.393
Yeah. she came in
and killed it from the start.

805
00:40:36.477 --> 00:40:39.563
Her audition was just bonkers.
you know. like.

806
00:40:39.647 --> 00:40:41.982
she was this character from the get-go.

807
00:40:42.816 --> 00:40:44.360
She... If I remember correctly.

808
00:40:44.443 --> 00:40:48.656
she was actually supposed
to be a different character. Originally.

809
00:40:48.739 --> 00:40:53.327
She was cast as something.
I think. in season 4.

810
00:40:53.410 --> 00:40:55.663
and then for whatever reason
couldn't end up doing it.

811
00:40:55.746 --> 00:41:00.668
But we remembered her audition.
and we remembered her as an actor

812
00:41:00.751 --> 00:41:02.795
just being incredible.

813
00:41:02.878 --> 00:41:05.255
And so when it came time
to cast the Progenitor.

814
00:41:05.923 --> 00:41:08.634
I remember just being.
"Oh. well. it's got to be her."

815
00:41:08.717 --> 00:41:10.052
- That's right.
- Yeah.

816
00:41:10.761 --> 00:41:14.348
- So full of grace and...
- Yeah.

817
00:41:14.431 --> 00:41:15.891
...and regality.

818
00:41:16.433 --> 00:41:17.726
That's. like. that's it.

819
00:41:17.810 --> 00:41:22.523
Like. she has to carry this.
like. the weight of the character

820
00:41:22.606 --> 00:41:26.402
and the years and the role.

821
00:41:26.485 --> 00:41:29.446
And it's all right there in her eyes.
It's really...

822
00:41:30.656 --> 00:41:31.740
And you can see her eyes

823
00:41:31.824 --> 00:41:34.201
beneath all the prosthetics
that she had to sit through.

824
00:41:34.284 --> 00:41:36.078
That's right. That's right.

825
00:41:36.161 --> 00:41:39.081
And Anthony Tran.
our new costume designer.

826
00:41:39.164 --> 00:41:41.125
you know. there at the tail end after...

827
00:41:42.167 --> 00:41:43.961
he was beloved. so brilliant...

828
00:41:44.044 --> 00:41:47.673
after our beloved and brilliant
Gersha Phillips left. you know.

829
00:41:47.756 --> 00:41:50.134
He did such a beautiful job
here too with her.

830
00:41:50.217 --> 00:41:52.428
- I mean. with all of us...
- Yeah.

831
00:41:52.511 --> 00:41:54.096
...but with her too.

832
00:41:54.179 --> 00:41:58.475
You just... You just see it.
you feel it. you get it.

833
00:42:00.477 --> 00:42:02.563
And our... And shout-out
to our prosthetics team.

834
00:42:02.646 --> 00:42:04.523
Glenn and his team.

835
00:42:04.606 --> 00:42:11.071
with. like. taking the original.
like. idea for the Progenitors.

836
00:42:11.155 --> 00:42:12.823
and then updating it a little bit

837
00:42:13.907 --> 00:42:16.547
and just. I mean. all the prosthetics
all the way around. you know.

838
00:42:16.577 --> 00:42:23.125
that brings our nonhuman creature...
people... species to life.

839
00:42:24.001 --> 00:42:28.255
Yeah. because it's... You know.
the prosthetics are... work on two fronts.

840
00:42:28.922 --> 00:42:33.469
On the first front. the...
it's the actor's ability

841
00:42:33.552 --> 00:42:37.723
to act beneath all of that silicone
and make it come to life

842
00:42:37.806 --> 00:42:42.561
and having to sometimes overact
in order to get it to come out.

843
00:42:43.103 --> 00:42:44.563
And Doug has...

844
00:42:44.646 --> 00:42:47.441
has taught me a lot about
what goes on underneath that...

845
00:42:47.524 --> 00:42:48.525
underneath that rubber.

846
00:42:48.609 --> 00:42:50.652
It's quite... It's quite impressive.

847
00:42:50.736 --> 00:42:52.362
And then on the other front.

848
00:42:52.446 --> 00:42:55.491
the prosthetics have to be able
to allow the actors to emote

849
00:42:55.574 --> 00:42:59.119
while also looking like the alien species
that we want them to look like.

850
00:42:59.203 --> 00:43:03.040
And I think Glenn has just been
masterful over the years for us with that...

851
00:43:03.123 --> 00:43:06.168
- Yeah.
- ...in being able to find that balance

852
00:43:06.251 --> 00:43:09.087
and that flexibility within the makeup.

853
00:43:09.171 --> 00:43:15.761
Yeah. And it does take really just
special actors to be able to do that.

854
00:43:17.221 --> 00:43:20.724
Somkele. Doug. of course. Elias...

855
00:43:22.476 --> 00:43:24.311
- David.
- ...David. Yeah.

856
00:43:24.394 --> 00:43:27.898
Just all of our actors under all of that

857
00:43:27.981 --> 00:43:31.568
- to be able to bring out the characters.
- Yeah.

858
00:43:32.694 --> 00:43:36.281
And then Hannah Cheesman
and Sara Mitich who were both Airiam.

859
00:43:36.365 --> 00:43:37.825
- Them too.
- Yes.

860
00:43:37.908 --> 00:43:41.620
And then obviously Mary Chieffo
and Shazad with the. you know.

861
00:43:41.703 --> 00:43:45.999
way back in our early days.
they played Klingons.

862
00:43:46.083 --> 00:43:50.671
It's like. man. people don't realize
how difficult what they do really is.

863
00:43:52.214 --> 00:43:54.495
Like. a lot of... Like you said.
it takes a special actor.

864
00:43:54.550 --> 00:43:56.653
A lot of actors would just simply
not be able to do it.

865
00:43:56.677 --> 00:43:58.887
It's a big part of the reality. isn't it?

866
00:43:58.971 --> 00:44:01.682
Because. like.
we're dealing with stuff that...

867
00:44:01.765 --> 00:44:03.141
it's sci-fi. it doesn't exist.

868
00:44:03.225 --> 00:44:05.853
And. you know.
sci-fi is an allegory for real life.

869
00:44:05.936 --> 00:44:09.731
but it's not real until we look
at these faces

870
00:44:09.815 --> 00:44:12.192
- and they tell us it's real. right?
- Yeah.

871
00:44:12.276 --> 00:44:14.778
No matter what you do. like.
it all comes back down...

872
00:44:14.862 --> 00:44:18.156
the gravity. the way it all works...
it comes back down to their performance.

873
00:44:18.240 --> 00:44:21.618
and how believable they're making
that performance in the moment.

874
00:44:22.703 --> 00:44:25.539
Yeah. And the actor who plays Grudge.

875
00:44:25.622 --> 00:44:26.707
Oh. Grudge.

876
00:44:27.749 --> 00:44:29.167
Yeah. I mean...

877
00:44:29.251 --> 00:44:32.337
That day I found out
there were two Grudges...

878
00:44:34.464 --> 00:44:35.549
That's the funniest.

879
00:44:35.632 --> 00:44:38.069
- That's still one of my favorite stories.
- That was too funny.

880
00:44:38.093 --> 00:44:39.093
Yeah. Yeah.

881
00:44:39.094 --> 00:44:42.264
If you haven't heard it.
I'll repeat it here. you know.

882
00:44:42.347 --> 00:44:44.099
which was. you know. we were ha...

883
00:44:44.182 --> 00:44:45.601
Grudge was acting up one day.

884
00:44:45.684 --> 00:44:48.979
and I was trying to get Grudge
to do a particular thing

885
00:44:49.062 --> 00:44:51.106
on set with David.

886
00:44:51.189 --> 00:44:53.233
and it just wasn't happening.

887
00:44:53.317 --> 00:44:57.112
Grudge was not listening to the director.

888
00:44:57.195 --> 00:45:02.367
and... and then...
and then the wrangler says.

889
00:45:02.451 --> 00:45:04.661
"Well. how about if we use the other one?"

890
00:45:04.745 --> 00:45:09.791
And I'm. "What are you talking about.
the other one?"

891
00:45:09.875 --> 00:45:13.795
"Yeah. his brother." you know. I'm like...

892
00:45:13.879 --> 00:45:15.047
And then David comes out

893
00:45:15.130 --> 00:45:18.300
and David was like.
"Yeah. Why don't you use the other one?"

894
00:45:18.383 --> 00:45:21.553
So David knew the whole time
there were two.

895
00:45:21.637 --> 00:45:23.347
Wasn't this season 4?

896
00:45:23.430 --> 00:45:26.266
Like. we had had Grudge all of season 3

897
00:45:26.350 --> 00:45:29.144
and now we're halfway into season 4
when you find out.

898
00:45:29.227 --> 00:45:31.480
- Yeah.
- It was Leeu and Durban.

899
00:45:31.563 --> 00:45:34.316
- I remember their names.
- Oh. my gosh. how do you remember that?

900
00:45:34.399 --> 00:45:37.611
Yo. because Leeu was the older brother
who didn't want to be there.

901
00:45:37.694 --> 00:45:42.532
- And Durban was sweet and. you know...
- More chilled. yeah.

902
00:45:42.616 --> 00:45:45.285
- Oh. my gosh.
- David...

903
00:45:45.369 --> 00:45:48.163
David took a lot of...
took a lot of heat from Leeu.

904
00:45:48.664 --> 00:45:51.625
Listen. listen.
And my heart is still open.

905
00:45:52.668 --> 00:45:54.920
Oh. man. that cat works on me sometimes.

906
00:45:55.712 --> 00:45:57.923
- Seriously.
- I love this moment between them.

907
00:45:58.006 --> 00:46:00.175
- I love all their moments.
- Yeah.

908
00:46:00.258 --> 00:46:03.220
I mean. goodness. Mary is just
one of the most...

909
00:46:03.303 --> 00:46:06.473
one of the most exceptional actors
I've ever... I've ever worked with.

910
00:46:06.556 --> 00:46:08.433
Yes. 100%.

911
00:46:08.517 --> 00:46:10.394
She can... She can do anything.

912
00:46:12.020 --> 00:46:13.230
Agreed.

913
00:46:15.857 --> 00:46:18.193
But I love how their dynamic...

914
00:46:18.276 --> 00:46:21.613
specifically Rayner and Tilly...

915
00:46:21.697 --> 00:46:25.575
I love how their dynamic
grew and changed and...

916
00:46:25.659 --> 00:46:27.035
over the course of the season.

917
00:46:27.995 --> 00:46:28.996
It was really fun...

918
00:46:29.079 --> 00:46:34.042
Episode 4 of this season. in particular.
I thought was really cool.

919
00:46:34.126 --> 00:46:37.087
When you were talking about Mary...
Just watching her play.

920
00:46:37.170 --> 00:46:40.424
who she was in season 1 versus now.

921
00:46:40.507 --> 00:46:43.719
And you. Who you were in season 1
versus who you are now.

922
00:46:44.678 --> 00:46:47.264
All the characters. really.

923
00:46:47.347 --> 00:46:52.269
And it just was such a. like...
It was such a fascinating thing

924
00:46:52.352 --> 00:46:56.940
to watch you as actors go back at.
and then play where you are now.

925
00:46:57.816 --> 00:46:58.984
Yeah.

926
00:47:07.284 --> 00:47:09.036
David. I gotta ask.

927
00:47:09.119 --> 00:47:13.957
So. the last season your planet blew up.
Your home world blew up.

928
00:47:14.666 --> 00:47:19.087
This... This season. you know.
that didn't quite happen.

929
00:47:19.171 --> 00:47:21.315
but obviously it's still
in the history of your character.

930
00:47:21.339 --> 00:47:23.675
Like. you know.
what was the biggest difference

931
00:47:23.759 --> 00:47:29.014
you would say... if there was any...
between working these two seasons?

932
00:47:30.891 --> 00:47:34.478
Yeah. that's a great question. Tunde.

933
00:47:36.104 --> 00:47:40.942
I feel shooting season 5

934
00:47:41.526 --> 00:47:43.320
and that journey for Cleveland Booker.

935
00:47:43.403 --> 00:47:45.155
I think it was just...

936
00:47:45.864 --> 00:47:48.450
You realize that even though
this is someone dealing with...

937
00:47:50.160 --> 00:47:52.454
an immeasurable amount of grief.

938
00:47:52.537 --> 00:47:56.541
he also realizes how blessed he is
to be afforded a second chance.

939
00:47:57.626 --> 00:48:00.337
And I think when he's offered
that invitation.

940
00:48:01.088 --> 00:48:04.091
I think he grabs it with dear. dear life.

941
00:48:07.010 --> 00:48:09.137
I don't know. I think that there's a lot...

942
00:48:09.221 --> 00:48:12.891
Everyone at one point in their journey.
every character in the show.

943
00:48:12.974 --> 00:48:15.102
- has been given a second chance.
- Yes.

944
00:48:15.185 --> 00:48:19.773
And. you know. to see someone
"fall from grace."

945
00:48:19.856 --> 00:48:23.110
be afforded a second chance
to just be the better version.

946
00:48:23.193 --> 00:48:26.613
the best version of himself...
not the perfect version of himself.

947
00:48:26.696 --> 00:48:28.782
but the most authentic
version of himself...

948
00:48:28.865 --> 00:48:31.910
I think is a very special thing
to witness on screen.

949
00:48:31.993 --> 00:48:36.248
And I enjoyed. maybe...
I'm not sure if that's the right word.

950
00:48:36.331 --> 00:48:41.336
I felt very privileged to be given
that blessing to tell that story.

951
00:48:43.088 --> 00:48:45.465
It was a blessing to watch you
tell that story. David.

952
00:48:45.549 --> 00:48:50.428
I just... I just have to say. like. I...
You know. I big you up all the time.

953
00:48:50.512 --> 00:48:52.472
You probably are tired of it
at this point.

954
00:48:52.556 --> 00:48:54.099
I big you all up all the time.

955
00:48:54.182 --> 00:48:55.475
- But. man...
- No. no. no.

956
